data.content:
Yes — MSTest v3.3+ supports **typed data sources** via `TypedDataRow` and `[DataRowData]`/`[DynamicData]` with tuples, but the cleanest approach is the **`[TestDataSource]`** pattern with strongly-typed records:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string Input, bool Expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:** `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>`. MSTest v3.3+ `DynamicData` supports **tuples** and will decompose them into the method parameters.

**Other options depending on your MSTest version:**

| Approach | Minimum version |
|---|---|
| `IEnumerable<ValueTuple<...>>` with `[DynamicData]` | MSTest 3.3 |
| `[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]` inline attributes | MSTest 2.x (works for compile-time constants only) |

If your test data is all constants, `[DataRow]` is the simplest:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DataRow("valid@email.com", true)]
[DataRow("invalid", false)]
[DataRow("", false)]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}
```

The **tuple-based `DynamicData`** gives you type safety at the data source while keeping the flexibility of computed test data.
